  "name": "Anthropological Dance: The Body Politic",
  "description": "Every culture dances. This grammar maps dance traditions from six continents through the lens of function — why do people dance? Sacred ritual, social bonding, martial power, courtship, resistance, trance. From Sufi whirling to Afrobeat, from Balinese temple dance to New York voguing, each tradition encodes a culture's relationship to the body, to power, to the divine. Dance is the first language; this grammar is its dictionary.\n\nPUBLIC DOMAIN ILLUSTRATION REFERENCES: Henri Matisse, *La Danse* (1910). Edgar Degas, dance studies and pastels. Ancient Egyptian dance reliefs (Tomb of Nebamun, ~1350 BCE). Mughal miniature paintings of court dancers. Greek red-figure vase paintings of maenads and satyrs.",
  "grammar_type": "custom",
  "creator_name": "PlayfulProcess",
  "tags": ["dance", "anthropology", "embodiment", "ritual", "resistance", "trance", "social", "global", "sacred"],
  "roots": ["embodiment", "myth-and-symbol", "liberation"],
  "shelves": ["wonder", "resilience", "earth"],
  "lineages": ["Akomolafe", "Andreotti"],
  "worldview": "animist",
